{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_hawthorne_ver01/data/sn84026749/00205698255/1938011101/0655.xml":{"full_text":"WASHINGTON FORECAST\nRain or snow tonight; lowest about 34;\ntomorrow rain, warmer; colder tomorrow\nnight.\nNo. 17,624\nHouse Group Favors Keeping Business Tax\nNUCHOLSDEATH\nPROBED; PISANI\nSENT TO JAIL\nBail of Gambler\u2019s\nAide Revoked\ni\nBy JAMES J. CULLINANE\nWhile police continued their In\nvestigation of the death of Carroll\nPeyton \u201cNubby\u201d Nuchols. prohibi\ntion racketeer and gambler who\ndied Saturday with a bullet\nthrough his brain. Justice Jesse\nAdkins in District Court today sent\nLawrence F. Pisani, his first lieu\ntenant, to jail.\nBond on which Pisani had been\nat liberty pending an appeal from\na gambling conviction was revoked\nby Justice Adkins because Pisani\nhad been captured with Nuchols\nin a gambling raid last Thursday.\nATTENDED FUNERAL\nPi\u00bbni and Nuchols following\ntheir arrest last week were or\ndered to appear in court yester\nday to show cause why their\nbonds should not be revoked. Pi\nsani\u2019s attorneys explained their\nclient was absent from the city\nyesterday attending the funeral\nof Nuchols in Richmond, Va.\nWhispered rumors that Nuch\nols was murdered by underworld\nrivals led. detectives today to ana\nlyse the halidwritirig da the note\nfound with his body in which the\ngamble, asked the forgiveness of\nhis wife.\nSUICIDE IS BELIEF\nInspector Bernard W. Thomp\nson, chief of detectives, said the\nhandwriting on the note addressed\nto Nuchols\u2019 red-haired wife will\nbe checked with specimens of the\ngambler\u2019s handwriting, although\nhe Is convinced Nuchols com\nmitted suicide.\n\u201cWe are not leaving any loose\nends in this case,\u201d Inspector\nThompson said. \u201cWhen we got\nthe first flash on Nuckols\u2019 death,\nweb egan investigating it on the\ntheory he had been murdered,\nalthough all evidence at the\ntime pointed to suicide. We\ndid not accept the suicide theory\nuntil the coroner had performed\nan autopsy and found powder\nmarks inside the wound in\nNuckols\u2019 head and on his hand,\nWhich showed he had held the\ngun tightly against his temple.\u201d\nNuchols, it is known, had little\nmoney for several weeks before his\ndeath and it is reported he owed\nlarge sums to the gambler who\nwas drinking cocktails downtown\nwhen police reached the Connec\nticut Avenue apartment.\nRed Council Opens;\nDelegates \u2018Yokels\u2019\nMOSCOW, Jan. 11 (I.NS.).\nMany of them weary from long\nJourneys by donkey, camel and\nsled, delegates to Soviet Russia\u2019s\nnewly elected supreme council or\nparliament crowded Moscow to\nday for the scheduled opening of\nthe legislative body. Some of them\nhad never seen trains or automo\nbiles until they reached the capi\ntal.\nINDEX\nAndrew R. Kelley 20\nBirths and Marriages 18\nBoake Carter 17\nClassified Ads 23, 24, 25\nDrama 20\nEditorials 6\nEvalyn Walsh McLean 17\nFlora Macdonald 12\nFrank Buck\u201d O\u2019Neill 21\nHelen Essary 17\nInquiring Photographer _... 6\nJ. Earl Moser 11\nKirk Miller 21\nPaul Mallon 7\nPeter Carter 12\nRadio 19\nWomen\u2019s Page 10\nEntered Second Class Matter at\nPost Office at Washington, D. C.\nPosse Races Storm\nTo Air Crash Scene\nVdQl PLANB\nJjp; WN HERE\nh \u2022*\u2022\u00a3....A\nKite\nARROWS ON this map show the direction the doomed\nNorthwestern Airlines\u2019 Lockheed Zephyr was flying when\nit smashed into the Bridger Mountains, northeast of Boze\nman, Mont. The broken line shows the route the ship\nwas supposed to follow to Livingston and Billings.\nU. S. Launches Probe\nOs Montana Tragedy\nCosting 10 Lives\n(1.N.5.) A large group of Gov\nemment aeronautics experts con\nverged on Bozeman, Mont., -today\nto investigate the irash of a North\nwest Airlines passenger plane\nwhich brought death to 10 persons.\nThe following were ordered to\nthe crash scene by the Bureau\nof Air Commerce: R. I. Hazen, air\nline inspector of Chicago; A. D.\nNiemeyer, air line inspector, Spo\nkane; O. A. Rosto, air line mainte\nnance inspector, Salt Lake City;\nMonte Snedeker, air line inspector,\nSt. Paul; R. Nee, airway mechani\ncian, Salt Lake City, and F. H.\nStevens, air line radio inspector,\nof Los Angeles.\nBureau Director Fred Fagg an\nnounced a Federal board of in\nquiry would be named later.\nBOZEMAN, Mont., Jan. 11\n(1.N.5.). \u2014A 100-foot circle burned\ninto the snow marked the lonely\nmountainside spot today where 10\npersons met a flaming death in\nthe crash of their luxury airliner.\nFaced with the chance of a sud\nden blizzard that would erase the\nsite and perhaps bury the victims\nfor months, ranchers and rangers\nstarted out early to bring back the\nmangled and charred bodies on\nmuleback.\nCAUSE SOUGHT\nPressed by the same emergency,\nGovernment and airline officials\nhurried here to inspect the bits of\ntwisted wreckage in the hope of\nsolving the secret of the disas\nter.\nSix passengers and four com\npany employes perished when the\nnew Lockheed Zephyr of the\nNorthwest Airlines plunged into a\ncraggy slope of the Bridger Moun\ntain range northeast of here late\nyesterday. They were:\nLieut. Nick Marner of Spokane,\nWash., the pilot; Fred West, also\nof Spokane, co-pilot; A. H. Croon\nquist, Montana traffic manager of\n(Continued on Page 2, Col. 2)\nD. C. Attorney Is Ordered\nTo Jail on Wife\u2019s Charges\nBart Clinss, a local attorney\nwith offices in the Columbian\nBuilding, was adjudged in con\ntempt of court by Justice Jen\nnings Bailey in United States\nDistrict Court today and ordered\ncommitted to jail for 30 days for\nfailing to comply with an order\ndirecting him to make mainten-\n\nTHE CAPITAL'S A I J-1\nRMW\nPILOT MAMER\nFORMER GIANT\nHELD IN MURDER\nSAULT STE. MARIE, Ontario,\nJan. 11 (I.N.S.).\u2014Vernon Spencer,\n40-year-old Michigan dairy farmer\nand former outfielder for the New\nYork Giants, was in the shadow of\nthe gallows today.\nAuthorities said he must stand\ntrial for his life at the spring\nassizes on a charge of murdering\nHelen Grier, pretty 28-year-old\nPontiac (Mich.) stenographer, in a\nlonely, north woods cabin during a\nprojected hunting trip last fall.\nHouse to Summon\nJudge and DJ.Men\n(1.N.5.) The House Judiciary\nCommittee today voted to investi\ngate the conduct of both Federal\nJudge Ferdinand A. Geiger of\nMiwaukee and the Department of\nJustice in a grand jury probe of\nalleged monopolistic practices of\nthe automobile business.\nSnow or Rain Due\nToday and Tonight\nWashington had its first taste\nof winter today, when snow\nstarted falling, with a prospect of\nsnow or rain all day and tonight.\nThe temperature is expected to\ndrop to a low of 34 degrees to\nnight, with clearing weather and\nwarmer temperatures tomorrow.\nance payments to his wife and\nfive children.\nHis wife, Mrs. Edna C. Clines,\n1519 Thirty-fifth St. N. W., sued\nhim for maintenance last July\nand won a $25 monthly main\ntenance award with which Clines,\nit is alleged, has not complied.\nA total of $2Ol in delinquent\npayments has accrued,\nTUESDAY, JANUARY 11, 1938\nLYNCHING BILL\nTHREATENS T 0\nSPLIT PARTY\nSouthern Foes Set\nFor Long Fight\nBy ARTHUR HACHTEN\n(1.N.5.) Southern Senators\ncontinuing their fight against the\nanti-lynching bill in the Senate\ntoday solemnly declared the meas\nure threatens to split the Demo\ncratic party wide open.\nSenator Byrnes (D.), South\nCarolina, swung into the bitter\nwarfare with a blunt assertion the\nmeasure has put the torch to\n\u201csectional hatreds,\u201d and threatens\nto \u201cdestroy the Democratic party.\u201d\nSET FOR LONG FIGHT\nIndignation of Dixie, fanned by\nthe wage-hours bill, reached the\nboiling point in today\u2019s skirmish\ning over the Wagner-Van Nuys\nanti-lynching bill. Attempts by\nsupporters of the measure to\nround up a two-thirds majority to\napply the cloture or gag rule and\nforce a vote, proved futile. Repub\nlicans and Democrats balked at\nthat drastic procedure.\nSo the Southern foes of the\nmeasure settled down for a long\nsiege. They served notice they\nwill talk in relays against the bill\nin an effort to stave off a vote.\nCITES STATE LAWS\nByrnes in pleading against \u201cin\nvasion of State powers,\u201d told the\nSenate murder is punishable by\ndeath in every State.\n\u201cThe only justification then\nfor this bill must be that the pro\nponents of it think that the\nStates are not enforcing their\nlaws against murder,\u201d said\nByrnes. \u201cThey want the Fed\neral Government to do it,\u201d he\nsaid.\n\u201cThis should be called a bill\nto arouse ill-feeling between the\nsections of the country and a bill\nto destroy the Democratic\nparty.\u201d\nCONNALLY FIRM\nThough Administration leaders\nhave indicated they would begin\ncracking down on the filibus\ntered this week, with night as\nwell as day sessions in an effort to\nwear out the opposition. Majority\nLeader Barkley of Kentucky, said\nno decision had been reached on\nwhen to force the night sessions.\nSEE WHAT HAPPENS\n\u201cWe are going to let the de\nbate run along awhile and then\nsee what happens,\u201d said Bark\nley.\nWith the'housing and farm bills\nlocked in conference with the\nHouse, Barkley noted the Gov\nernment reorganization measure is\nthe only major piece of legislation\nready for consideration in the\nSenate.\nSenators Russell (D.) of Geor\ngia, and Byrnes (D.) of South\nCarolina, took up the warfare\nagainst the anti-lynching bill to\nday, with Senator Reynolds (D.)\nof North Carolina, standing by to\ntake the floor any time a speaker\nis needed to prevent a vote.\nReynolds has spoken on the bill\nevery one of the four days it has\nbeen debated in the Senate. The\nNorth Carolinian declared himself\nprepared to speak \u201cfor many\nhours\u201d if needed.\nJuliana Awaits\nSir Stork\u2019s Visit\nAMSTERDAM, Jan. 11 (1.N.5.).\nThe visit from Sir Stork, that all\nHolland is joyfully anticipating,\nis scheduled to be made about one\nor two weeks hence. Such was\nthe news in an official com\nmunique issued today by Crown\nPrincess Juliana\u2019s secretary.\nFarm Outlook Dark,\nWallace Tells Senate\nCommittee Advised\nRelief Needs to\nBe Larger\nBy ROBERT A. McGILL\n(1.N.5.) Recommending addi\ntional funds for relief, Secretary\nof Agriculture Wallace today\npainted a drab outlook for the\nfarmer before the Senate Com\nmittee investigating the business\nrecession.\nDeclaring that if money were\navailable, the farm rehabilitation,\nprogram could be expanded to,\ntwo or three times its present size.\nWallace said:\n\u201cWe are facing an urgent ne\ncessity for expanding rural re\nlief. The demand for Federal\naid is being augmented daily by\na variety of factors \u2014notably an\nimpending drought in certain\nareas, sagging farm prices, the\nrapid mechanization of agricul\nture and the industrial reces\nsion.\u201d\nLUMBER STUDIED\nIn addition, the committee ex\npects to survey the lumber busi\nness. Wilson Compton, president\nof the National Lumber Manufac\nturers Association, will testify.\nLeonard P. Ayres, Cleveland econ\nomist, is also scheduled to appear.\nJohn L. Lewis, chairman of the\nCIO, will testify later in the\nweek.\nThe committee asked the prin\ncipal automobile manufacturers to\nsubmit a month-by-month record\nof employment for the year 1937.\nThis move was taken after Homer\nL. Martin, president of the United\nAutomobile Workers, a CIO affil\niate, cited figures that failed to\ncorrespond with recent Census rec\nords, and statements by William\nS. Knudsen, president of General\nMotors. Martin estimated employ\nment in the automobile industry\nhad fallen off 50 per cent, while\nthe committee\u2019s temporary survey\nshowed less than half of that\namount.\nLAY OFFS CHECKED\nChairman Byrnes (D.) of South\nCarolina, said also he wanted to\ncheck Martin on statements that\nGeneral Motors had been laying\noff men steadily before the recent\nannouncement that 30,000 had\nbeen dropped from the giant cor\nporation\u2019s payroll, and 205,000\nothers had been placed on a 24-\nhour work week.\nThe automobile companies to be\nqueried are General Motors, Chrys\nler, Ford, Hudson and Stude\nbaker.\nByrnes said he had no quarrel\nwith either Knudsen or Martin,\n(Continued on Page 2, Col. 1)\nCensor Frowns\nOn Shirley Temple\nBLOOMINGTON, 111., Jan. 11\n(I.N.S.).\u2014Shirley Temple today\nbecame the latest to meet a cen\nsor\u2019s frown here. Mrs. Leslie\nErnst, chairman of the city\u2019s bet\nter movies committee, said the\nchild star\u2019s picture, \u201cThe Little\nRebel,\u201d had upset many young\nsters because she was cast with\ntoo many adults.\nDIES IN PLUNGf\nNEW YORK, Jan. 11 (1.N.5.).\nA man who leaped or fell to his\ndeath from a Midtown Building\nhere late yesterday was identified\ntoday as Carl Rogge, 45, of Bush\nbill Falls. Pa.\nJustice Cardozo Weaker\nAfter Holding Own in Night\n(1.N.5.) Associate Justice Ben\njamin N. Cardozo, of the Supreme\nCourt, who is suffering from heart\ntrouble, today was reported \u201ca\ntrifle weaker\u201d than last night.\nK 4\n2. A.\nI\n14\ns gfe\nInternational New* Photo\nSECRETARY OF AGRICULTURE HENRY A. WAL-\nLACE was snapped as he told a Senate committee, investi\ngating the slump in business, that the outlook for the Ad\nministration\u2019s farm program\u2014and for American farmers\u2014\nis gloomy unless sufficient money is appropriated to carry\nthe program forward.\nSloan, Weir Visit\nWhite House Today\nBrown, Clement and Chester Also to Confer\nThis Afternoon With President\n(1.N.5.) President Roosevelt today summoned five of\nthe nation\u2019s outstanding industrial leaders to the White House\nfor a conference, on the causes of the current business recession\nand a discussion of possible remedies.\nThose who will meet with the*\nPresident at 5 p. m. are Alfred P.\nSloan, chairman of the board of\nGeneral Motors; Ernest P. Weir,\nchairman of the National Steel\nCompany; Lewis Brown, president\nof the Johns-Mansville Company;\nM. W. Clement, president of the\nPennsylvania railroad, and prob\nably Colby Chester, head of the\nNational Association of Manufac\nturers anad of General Foods.\nThe President conferred this\nmorning with Daniel C. Green, of\nthe General Service Corporation\nof Chicago; John Carpenter, of\nthe Texas Power and Light Com\npany, Dallas, and A. B. West, presi\ndent of the Nevada, California\nElectric Corporation.\nPrior to the meeting with the\nbusiness leaders, Mr. Roosevelt ob\ntained a last-minute report from\nAubrey Williams, acting WPA ad\nministrator, on relief rolls. Wil\nliams said since December 1 the\nWPA had added less than 300,000\nmen and women.\nThe administrator warned that\nthe greatest pressure would be felt\nby the Government relief agency\nabout February 1.\nGovernor Murphy of Michigan\nalso was scheduled to lunch with\nthe President today.\nA bulletin issued at 11:30 a. nj.\ntoday by Dr. John Paul Earnest\nsaid:\n\u2018\u2018The Justice is holding his\n1 own, although a trifle weaker\nthan last night.\u201d\nHOME\nE DITI ON\nMONEY!\nSays Farmers\nNeed It\nGrace Saves\n35,000 Jobs\nNEW YORK, Jan. 11 (1.N.5.).\nA work-sharing plan to save the\njobs of 35,000 employes was an\nnounced today by Eugene G.\nGrace, president of Bethlehem\nSteel Company.\nGrace also \u201ctalked back\u201d to\ncritics of industry and sharply\ncriticised the CIO steel workers\u2019!\norganizing committee.\nDeclaring that the corporation\naccepted principles of collective\nbargaining nearly 20 years ago, he\nasserted:\n\u201cThe company is defending\nitself (before the National\nLabor Relations Board) and at\nconsiderable expense against\nwhat we believe to be an un\nfounded charge made by the\nsteel workers\u2019 organizing com\nmittee that the company is\ndo m i nating collective-bargain\ning plans.\nExplaining the decision to\nspread out work opportunities,\nGrace reported that steel demand\n\u201chas reached a level approaching\nthat of the 1932-1935 depression.\u201d\nBasketball Star\nDies During Game\nSEYMOUR, Conn., Jan. 11\n(1.N.5.). \u2014Only 45 seconds before\nthe end of a semi-pro basketball\ngame, in which he played center,\nGeorge Bedors, 18, of this town,\ndropped dead. According to a\nreport filed today by Dr. E. R.\nHarvey and Dr. Louis Rogol,\ndeath was due to a heart attack.\nTHREE CENTS\nINCOME LEVY\nALSO FAVORED\nBY MEMBERS\nDirksen in Favor of\nNew Feature\nContinuation of the business\nprivilege tax and the $1.75 tax on\nreal estate will be provided in a\nnew tax bill to be introduced in\nthe House next week, it was an\nnounced today by Representative\nJack Nichols (D.) of Oklahoma,\nchairman of the House District\nFiscal Affairs Subcommittee.\nIn addition, an income tax may\nbe written into the bill to become\neffective a year from enactment of\nthe new tax measure.\nCONTINUE LEVIES\nDefinite assurance that the\npresent tax program, enacted last\nyear for emergency purposes, will\nbe continued In its present form\nwas given at the conclusion of\npreliminary hearings of the fiscal\naffairs subcommittee.\nAfter a session of less than an\nhour, when the District Commis\nsioners and District Auditor Dan\niel J. Donovan were heard briefly,\nthe subcommittee went into execu\ntive session with the local offi\ncials to begin preparation for\ndrafting the new measure.\nWhen the executive meeting\nbroke up. Representative Nichols\nannounced that the subcommittee\nwill meet Monday, put the bill into\nfinal shape, and that the measure\nprobably will be introduced in the\nHouse on Wednesday.\nHEARINGS SLATED\nPublic hearings on the bill it\nself will begin the following week,\nMr. Nichols announced, probably\na week from next Monday.\nIntroduction of the income tax\nfeature as a part of the bill grew\nout of a discussion led by Repre\nsentative Everett M. Dirksen (R.)\nof Illinois, ardent income tax ad\nvocate, who pointed to the recently\npublic list of salaries above $20,-\n000 as \u201cthe most informative docu\nment\u201d in support of tax on in\ncome.\nHe disputed the efficacy of a\nsales tax, recommended by the\nCommissioners\u2019 tax advisory com\nmittee, as a \u201cinequitable levy\u201d and\npointed to statistics showing that\nthe lower income group bears the\nbrunt of a sales tax.\nCiting statistics from a recent\nstudy he inserted in the record fig\nures showing that persons with an\nincome of SI,OOO paid annually\n$18.27 on the basis of a 3 per cent\nsales tax. In the same ratio per\nsons with an income of $2,000 pay\n[514.82; $3,000 to $5,000, pay $12.87;\nfrom SIO,OOO they pay $11.97, and\n$25,000, pay $9.51,\n\u201cThis shows,\u201d Mr. Dirksen\nsaid, \u201cwho pays the sales tax.\"\nOn the statement that repeal\nof the business privilege tax has\nbeen recommended by both the\nCommissioners\u2019 tax advisory com\nmittee and the citizens advisory\ncommittee on taxation, Represent\native Nichols told the committee\nthat he felt skeptical over the\ncitizens\u2019 protests on the tax on\nbusiness.\nFUNNY ATTITUDE\n\u2018\u2018lt seems a bit peculiar to\nme,\u201d he said, \u201cthat groups repre\nsenting business men and civic\norganizations should say \u2018we\nhave felt the pulse of the people\nand we find that they object to\nbusiness being bothered by this\ntax and we want to take on the\nburden ourselves.\u2019 That seems\nrather funny.\u201d\nMr. Nichols pointed out that\n1 there are two types of sales tax,\none which is concealed and the\nother apparent. In the District,\nunder the business privilege tax.\nhe said he felt confident that the\ntax on business would be passed\non to the consumers.","height":"25827","width":"20334"}}
